article.description:
Lisa Leslie had 16 points and nine rebounds and the Los Angeles Sparks rebounded from their first regular-season home loss in nearly two years with an 87-65 victory
over the Sacramento Monarchs on Friday night.
article.headline: Sparks rout Monarchs on heels of rare home loss
article.linkText: Sparks back on track after rare home defeat
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Sparks quickly returned to
the form that enabled them to win 28 consecutive regular-season
home games over a three-span.

	   The defending Women's National Basketball Association champions
never trailed and took a 21-point halftime lead en route to a 87-65
victory over the Sacramento Monarchs Friday night.

	   Lisa Leslie had 16 points and nine rebounds and DeLisha Milton
14 points and nine rebounds at the Staples Center.

	   Mwadi Mabika and Sophia Witherspoon each added 11 points and
Tamecka Dixon had 10 for the Sparks (13-2), whose regular-season
home court winning streak ended Sunday. The 60-58 loss to the
Houston Comets was their first home regular-season loss since July
11, 2000, when they played at the Great Western Forum in Inglewood.

	   "This is the type of intensity and the level we want to play at
home,'' Los Angeles coach Michael Cooper said. "That's why we had
a 28-game home winning streak. That loss definitely helped heighten
the intensity and the urgency of the win tonight.''

	   Los Angeles scored the game's first five points and made its
first three shots. Consecutive baskets by Leslie, Milton and Dixon
increased its lead to 17-8 5:31 into the game.

	   The Sparks broke the game open with a 15-2 run over a 2:57 span,
taking a 45-25 lead shortly before halftime. Reserve Nicky
McCrimmon had four points during the run, with five teammates also
scoring.

	   Los Angeles led 51-30 at halftime, making 17 of its 28 shots
from the field, all 14 free throws and outrebounding the Monarchs
18-4.

	   Sacramento made 12 of 26 first-half shots and both its free
throws.

	   "To bounce back like this was real good,'' Cooper said. "The
days in between helped. We had four days off and we really got a
chance to hone in and shed the loss.''

	   Cooper said he was especially satisfied by his team's free throw
shooting. The Sparks made 27 of 30 free throws, after making eight
of 14 against Houston.

	   Los Angeles led by at least 20 and as many as 31 in the second
half. Nikki Teasley's 3-pointer capped a 15-4 run that gave Los
Angeles a 74-43 lead with 7:53 to play. The Monarchs responded by
scoring 12 of the next 14 points.

	   Kedra Holland-Corn scored 18, Tangela Smith 10 and Ruthie Bolton
16 off the bench for Sacramento (2-13).

	   "We didn't play at all the first half,'' Monarchs coach Maura
McHugh said. "I don't think we've done that this season."

	   Sacramento has lost seven consecutive games since point guard
Ticha Penicheiro was sidelined because of a right shoulder sprain.

	   The Monarchs also played without two other starters from last
year's team which reached the Western Conference finals. Forward
Yolanda Griffith (cervical disc bulge) and guard Edna Campbell
(cancer) are both on the injured list.

	   Griffith and Penicheiro were both starters in the 2001 WNBA
All-Star Game.
